 they speaking in contradistinction to?\" If kenon is called existent + real, then that which is existent + real is everywhere, so a continuum is presumed made up of the corporeal (to on) + the incorporeal (kenon or to den). All I can presume is that the concept of continuum must have obtained prior to the Atomists or they would have simply called the void what we call it: empty space containing nothing. But this is meden. This is what the Atomists refrain from calling the kenon. This is what they denied it: the status of meden. But it has in fact that status. To call the void \"existent + real\" is inexplicable, as Aristotle realized. Something is wrong. It, as an assertion, can only be meaningful in terms of prior perceptions + conceptions, because it is not meaningful to those later on (such as Aristotle). What I see is that the Atomists had to yield pro forma to the continuum view while still making their point. This was the only way they could make their point within the conceptual framework of the time. So those prior to the Atomists must have seen a continuum, +, if so, what did they see (or conceive) when they saw kenon? Physical objects? That literally touched each other? I can only speak on the basis of 3-74 at the time when I saw what I called Valis. How shall I describe it? I can't. There was one \"thing,\" that is, unity. +, being perceived + conceived as a unity, space (kenon) signified something other than what it signifies -ie is- in the discontinuous matter view. The key term is Gestalt. Each thing (what we call \"thing\") was not a thing at all; it was a part, + functioned as a part (of a whole). folder 53 - 002 folder 53 - 002 A-2 My mind filled in the kenon functionally. (1) The kenon had no significance. Here is where the Atomists enter. They consign significance to the kenon in contradistinction to to on, physical objects. The two are bipolarized. Kenon is viewed as existent + real in order that it divide off the physical objects (to on). This 